Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Lithuania. The Lithuanian authorities have introduced a number of measures to limit the spread of the virus.
Travel restrictions
The Lithuanian government has declared quarantine over the entire territory of Lithuania, effective from 00:00 EET Monday 16 March until 12:00 EET 30 March.
For information on how to return to the UK from Lithuania, see Return to the UK
British nationals without Lithuanian residency are not permitted to enter the country whilst quarantine measures are in place. Those with Lithuanian residency may enter the country but must isolate themselves for 14 days.
Transit of persons returning to their place of residence through Lithuania will be allowed until 00:00 EET on 23 March on condition they cross without any non-essential stops. Movement of goods is not restricted.
The border may be crossed at the following international border crossing points: Kalvarija - Budzisko, Saločiai - Grenstalė, Butingė - Rucava, Smėlynė - Medume, Medininkai - Kamenyi Log, Raigardas - Privalka, Kybartai - Chernyshevskoye, Panemunė - Sovetsk, Vilnius, Kaunas and Palanga airports and Klaipėda State Seaport. Klaipėda State Seaport is closed to cruise ships.
Keep up to date with information from your tour operator, transport or accommodation provider on the impact on any existing travel plans
If you need further information about entry requirements, contact the local immigration authorities or the nearest Lithuanian embassy/consulate. You should also check with your airline or travel company for the latest information.
Local measures
During the period of quarantine, the following arrangements on provision of healthcare apply:
Provision of inpatient personal health care services:
postponement of scheduled operations, except to provide first aid and emergency treatment
postponement of scheduled hospitalisations for diagnostic and therapeutic services
visits to patients shall be prohibited, except patients in terminal condition and children under 14 years of age, with the permission of the treating physician
restriction on the provision of medical rehabilitation services, except where failure to do so would result in a patient’s disability
Provision of outpatient health care services:
essential remote medical and dental services will continue, including provision of prescription medicines and medical aids, outpatient nursing and palliative care. But non-urgent and non-essential services will not be available
Shops may continue selling food, veterinary supplies, pharmacy and optical goods. Online sales and the delivery of goods are permitted.
The activities of catering facilities, restaurants, cafes, bars, nightclubs and other entertainment venues is prohibited, except where food can be taken away or otherwise delivered to customers.
Further details on Lithuania’s response to the COVID-19 pandemic are available in English on the Lithuanian Ministry of Foreign Affairs website.
Further information
Further information on coronavirus, including advice on preparing for foreign travel and helping reduce the spread of the virus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website
